{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "648b5a70417cc3fb48d683e7", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 3, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": 180, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "1", "classes": [], "exams": ["615d76b2c52ffa3c944600df"], "subjects": ["615d708dbd4a37c4058ee5a8"], "chapters": ["615d6fec2b295b085ab6eb92"], "topics": [], "concepts": [], "microConcepts": [], "questionLabels": [], "previousYearPapers": [{"_id": "648b5a3a0d9d0b909f7b648e", "title": "JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)", "isVisible": true}], "question": {"text": "<p>Given below are two statements:</p><p><strong>Statement I:</strong> If<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>be the total energy of a satellite moving around the earth, then its potential energy will be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>E</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>.</p><p><strong>Statement II:</strong> The kinetic energy of a satellite revolving in an orbit is equal to the half the magnitude of total energy <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi></math>.</p><p>In the light of the above statements, choose the most appropriate answer from the options given below.</p>", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "2GdJT", "text": "Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "pmkTI", "text": "Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "QRBnH", "text": "Both Statement I and Statement II are correct", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "aGj8b", "text": "Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "<blockquote><p>Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math>&nbsp;be the mass of the satellite.</p><p>The potential energy of the satellite is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>The velocity of the satellite is given by&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p>Kinetic energy is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>The total mechanical energy is the sum of potential and kinetic energy. So,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence, both the statements are false.</p></blockquote>", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "masterId": "MOGJMPYQ01423214", "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "bucket": "Easy Ques (Board Level)", "isRemoved": false, "cpyqbSubjects": ["61bb58181213731910ea0b70", "61c055eae8ce0dc8a5c62d33", "616057750283de43c87e3e1b", "61964fe0a5a5260118868021", "61964f81a5a526011886801d", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625b", "616057920283de43c87e3e1e", "615f0c729476412f48314dab", "61a8a2c2e8ce0dc8a5c62d2d", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352b", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7d", "616056cd0283de43c87e3e15", "